Exploratory Data Analysis with ggvis

Examples with Howells Craniometric Data

Trey Batey

2016-11-14

First steps

First, load a few necessary packages.

packs <- c('dplyr', 'ggvis', 'googlesheets', 'ggmap', 'rgdal', 'scales', 'tufte')
lapply(packs, require, character.only = TRUE)

Grab some data

I have a number of datasets stored as Google Sheets. How can I access them with R? Luckily, the googlesheets package provides an interface for working with Google Sheets. The code below creates an object (a dataframe called “howells”) by retrieving and reading in a spreadsheet with W. W. Howells’ craniometric data (Howells 1996Howells, WW. 1996. “Howells’ Craniometric Data on the Internet.” American Journal of Physical Anthropology 101 (3): 441–42. http://dx.doi.org/10.1002/ajpa.1331010302.).1 Dr. Ben Auerbach provides access to the digital data files.

howells <- gs_url('https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1GJNkJlYmq7MT1QmjRnQE2ptCxHYXt1OqgEfmLaAWCAg/edit?usp=sharing') %>% gs_read()

From 1965 to 1980, Howells collected craniometric data on 2524 human crania representing 28 populations from various parts of the world. He recorded up to 89 measurements per cranium and published results of his analyses in a series of three monographs (Howells 1973Howells, WW. 1973. “Cranial Variation in Man. A Study by Multivariate Analysis of Patterns of Difference Among Recent Human Populations.” In Papers of the Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology, 67:1–259. Cambridge, Mass.: Peabody Museum., Howells (1989Howells, WW. 1989. “Skull Shapes and the Map: Craniometric Analyses in the Dispersion of Modern Homo.” In Papers of the Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology, 79:1–189. Cambridge, Mass.: Peabody Museum.), Howells (1995Howells, WW. 1995. “Who’s Who in Skulls.” In Papers of the Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology. Vol. 82. Cambridge, Mass.: Peabody Museum.)). We can use the str() function to quickly look at the structure of the data

str(howells, list.len = 10)  ## A quick look of the structure of the data

Looking at the above ouput, we see that Howells also recorded the estimated sex and population represented for each individual. Let’s take the first measurement, glabella-occipital length (GOL) and plot the distribution as a histogram.

howells %>% ggvis(x = ~GOL) %>% layer_histograms(opacity:=1/3)
  • Renderer: SVG | Canvas
  • Download

We may naturally group our sample by sex and explore how males and females vary with respect to any one or more measurements. Staying with GOL…

howells %>% ggvis(x = ~GOL) %>% group_by(Sex) %>% layer_histograms(fill = ~Sex, opacity:=1/3)
  • Renderer: SVG | Canvas
  • Download

Or, we may want to graphically explore the relationship between two variables. For example, let’s look at maximum cranial length (glabella-occipital length, GOL) and maximum cranial breadth (XCB).

howells %>% ggvis(x = ~GOL, y = ~XCB) %>% group_by(Sex) %>% layer_points(fill = ~Sex, opacity:=1/3)
  • Renderer: SVG | Canvas
  • Download
